fields.description:
As per the title, when you have a build which generates artifacts or caches, if these are passed to the next step, their file permissions would always look like this, regardless of any file permissions on the previous step:
{code:java}
-rw-r--r-- {code}
 

This is disruptive as it may cause builds to fail due to file permissions being incorrect on the next step.

 

This feature request is to always keep the same file permissions on artifacts and caches when passing these from one step to the other.

 

The workaround for this, for now, would be to set the appropriate permissions manually on the step that receives the artifact using chmod.

h3. Issue Summary

Utilities like '*wget*', '*fetch'* (FreeBSD based utility) don't work when downloading content from Bitbucket account using app-password on private repositories.

The following two combinations doesn't work at this time:
 * wget + app_password + downloading_file_from_Private_Repo
 * fetch + app_password + downloading_file_from_Private_Repo

h3. Steps to Reproduce
{code:java}
wget --user=<user name> --password=<App password> -S "https://bitbucket.org/<Repo_Owner>/<Repo_Slug>/downloads/<filename>" -O "<filename>" 
{code}
{code:java}
fetch -vvo - https://<username>:<app_password>@api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<account_name>/<repo_name>/src/master/<filename>
{code}
 - 'wget' and 'fetch' both doesn't work with App password or HTTPS password with API endpoints for Private repos and returns "_{color:#ff8b00}ERROR 403: Forbidden{color}_" irrespective of valid or invalid authentications.

h3. Workaround

*1.* Use Curl command with App password and API endpoints:
{code:java}
curl -u <user_name>:<App_Pwd> -S -L "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<Repo_Owner>/<Repo_Slug>/downloads/<filename>" --output "<filename>" {code}
*2.* Use *wget* with option "*--auth-no-challenge*":
{code:java}
wget --http-user <username> --password <app-password> --auth-no-challenge https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<owner>/<repo-slug>/<path-to-file>{code}
It currently works with 'api.bitbucket.org'

+Working Combinations:+
 * wget + normal_password + downloading_file_within_repository (Private/Public Repo)
 * wget + app_password + downloading_file_within_repository (Public Repo)
 * fetch + normal_password + downloading_file_within_repository (Private/Public Repo)
 * fetch + app_password + downloading_file_within_repository (Public Repo)

When trying to run a pipeline, it failed after almost 20 minutes in the Build setup step with the following message:

 
19m 45s
 
{{+ umask 000}}
{{+ GIT_LFS_SKIP_SMUDGE=1 git clone --branch="master" --depth 50 [https://x-token-auth:$REPOSITORY_OAUTH_ACCESS_TOKEN@bitbucket.org/$BITBUCKET_REPO_FULL_NAME.git] $BUILD_DIR}}
{{Cloning into '/opt/atlassian/pipelines/agent/build'...}}
{{error: RPC failed; curl 18 transfer closed with outstanding read data remaining}}
{{fatal: The remote end hung up unexpectedly}}
{{fatal: early EOF}}
{{fatal: index-pack failed}}
 
Can you please add some sort of timeout so that it doesn't hang 20 minutes on a failed curl command?

h3. Problem

It can be quite useful to declare some general parameters in the global account a reference them in repository variables.

If for instance, we declare the following ones in the account area:
{code:java}
SERVICE_1_PORT=8080
SERVICE_2_PORT=8081{code}
 

And then declare the following one in the repository area:
{code:java}
THIS_SERVICE_PORT=$SERVICE_1_PORT{code}
The variable _THIS_SERVICE_PORT_ will not have the value _8080_, but the literal _$SERVICE_1_PORT_.
h3. Workaround

Use the eval command to create a new variable with the correct value.

e.g.
{code:java}
- eval export SERVER_PORT=$THIS_SERVICE_PORT{code}
